# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: home-run
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:home-run/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:home-run/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:home-run/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:home-run/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:home-run/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:home-run/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:home-run/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:home-run/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:home-run/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:home-run/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:home-run/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:home-run/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:home-run/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:home-run/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:home-run/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:home-run/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:home-run/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:home-run/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:home-run/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:home-run/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:home-run/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:home-run/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:home-run/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:home-run/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:home-run/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:home-run/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:home-run/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:home-run/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:home-run/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:home-run/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:home-run/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:home-run/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:home-run/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:home-run/1930-brooklyn-robins-season] The **1930 Brooklyn Robins** were in first place from mid-May through mid-August but faded down the stretch and finished the season in fourth place.
[src:home-run/1930-brooklyn-robins-season] This team featured one of the best offensive players in the game in Babe Herman and one of the best pitchers in Hall of Famer Dazzy Vance.
[src:home-run/1930-brooklyn-robins-season] Herman was arguably the second-best National League hitter in 1930, after Hack Wilson.
[src:home-run/1930-brooklyn-robins-season] He finished in the top three in batting average, on-base percentage, and slugging percentage.
[src:home-run/1930-brooklyn-robins-season] He led the NL in ERA by more than a full run, at 2.61.
[src:home-run/1930-brooklyn-robins-season] Considering that 1930 was a great year for hitters, statistically, this number is far better than it actually seems.
[src:home-run/1930-brooklyn-robins-season] Vance was also second in strikeouts and anchored a pitching staff that allowed the fewest runs in the league.
[src:home-run/1931-major-league-baseball-season] The **1931 major league baseball season** began on April 14, 1931.
[src:home-run/1931-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 27, with the St.
[src:home-run/1931-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals and Philadelphia Athletics as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:home-run/1931-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 28th World Series on October 1 and ended with Game 7 on October 10.
[src:home-run/1931-major-league-baseball-season] In the second iteration of this World Series matchup (and a rematch of the previous year), the Cardinals defeated the Athletics, four games to three, capturing their second championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1926.
[src:home-run/1931-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Philadelphia Athletics from the 1930 season.
[src:home-run/1931-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season that the Baseball Writers' Association of America (BBWAA) selected a Most Valuable Player in each league.
[src:home-run/1931-major-league-baseball-season] The 1931 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:home-run/1931-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 22 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:home-run/1931-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the 1904 season (except for 1919) and would be used until 1961 in the American League and 1962 in the National League.
[src:home-run/1931-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day, April 14, featured all sixteen teams, the first time since the 1926 season.
[src:home-run/1931-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on September 27, which also saw all sixteen teams play on the final day continuing the trend which began the previous season.
[src:home-run/1931-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first time that both Opening Day and the final day of the season saw all sixteen teams play.
[src:home-run/1931-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 1 and October 10.
[src:home-run/1931-major-league-baseball-season] 9 tie games (5 in AL, 4 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:home-run/1931-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 1 and ended on October 10 with the St.
[src:home-run/1931-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals defeating the Philadelphia Athletics in the 1931 World Series in seven games.
[src:home-run/1931-major-league-baseball-season] Across 80 homes games, the Boston Red Sox played all 15 of their Sunday games at the Boston Braves home field of Braves Field (the remaining 65 home games were played at Fenway Park).
[src:home-run/1931-major-league-baseball-season] This was the last of three consecutive seasons playing all Sunday games at Braves Field and 3rd of four consecutive season playing some games at Braves Field.
[src:home-run/1931-major-league-baseball-season] This was the last of 31 consecutive seasons that the Cleveland Indians played at their inaugural field, League Park (they would play full seasons at the Park in 1934 and 1935, while 1932, and 1936 to 1946 saw home games split with Cleveland Stadium.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] The **1960 World Series** was the championship series of Major League Baseball's (MLB) 1960 season.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] The 57th edition of the World Series, it was a best-of-seven playoff that matched the National League (NL) champion Pittsburgh Pirates against the American League (AL) champion New York Yankees.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] In Game 7, Bill Mazeroski hit the series winning ninth-inning home run, the first time a winner-take-all World Series game ended with a home run, and the first World Series to end on a home run.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Mazeroski's home run gave the Pirates their third title overall and their first since 1925.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Despite losing the series, the Yankees scored 55 runs, the most runs scored by any one team in World Series history, and more than twice as many as the Pirates, who scored 27.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] The Yankees won three blowouts (16–3, 10–0, and 12–0), while the Pirates won four close games (6–4, 3–2, 5–2, and 10–9) to win the series.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] The Pirates' run differential of minus 28 is the lowest ever by any team, winner or loser, in a World Series.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] The Series MVP was Bobby Richardson of the Yankees, the only time in history that the award has been given to a member of the losing team, though the rules were different at this time.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Votes had to be in by the start of the 8th inning of Game 7, at which point the Yankees were in the lead, and this was the first time since the series MVP award was created in 1955 that the team leading at that point did not go on to win.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Richardson was also the first non-pitcher to be named MVP.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] This World Series featured seven past, present, or future league Most Valuable Players.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] The Yankees, winners of their 10th pennant in 12 years, outscored the Pirates 55–27 in this Series, out-hit them 91–60, out-batted them .338 to .256, hit 10 home runs to Pittsburgh's four (three of which came in Game 7), got two complete-game shutouts from Whitey Ford—and lost.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] The Pirates' inconsistent pitching and Yankees' manager Casey Stengel's controversial decision not to start Ford in Games 1 and 4 resulted in the peculiar combination of close games and routs.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Ford (Games 3 and 6) and Vern Law (Games 1 and 4) were excellent, while Pirates relief pitcher Roy Face was a major factor in Games 1, 4 and 5.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] The Yankees also committed twice as many errors as the Pirates in the series.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] The Yankees had 8 errors while the Pirates had four errors.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] The Yankees threw Art Ditmar against the Pirates' Vern Law (the NL Cy Young Award winner) in Game 1.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] In the top of the first inning, New York right fielder Roger Maris, the eventual 1960 AL MVP, drilled a home run off Law to give the Yankees a 1–0 lead.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] In the bottom half, however, the Pirates evened the score when Bill Virdon walked, stole second, advanced to third on an error by shortstop Tony Kubek, and scored on a double by eventual National League Most Valuable Player Dick Groat.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Bob Skinner then singled to drive in Groat and stole second, coming home on a single by Roberto Clemente.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] This was enough to compel Casey Stengel, the Yankee manager, to pull Ditmar in favor of Jim Coates, who finished the inning.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] In the fourth, New York cut the lead to one run when Maris singled, moved to second on a Mickey Mantle walk, took third on a fly out by Yogi Berra, and scored on a single by Bill Skowron.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] But the Pirates extended their lead to 5–2 in the fourth when Don Hoak walked and Bill Mazeroski homered.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Game 2, matching New York's Bob Turley against the Pirates' Bob Friend, saw the Yankees pummel Pittsburgh 16–3.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] The game was scoreless until the top of the third, when the Yankees jumped out to a 2–0 lead.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Second baseman Bobby Richardson walked, was sacrificed over to second by Turley, and scored on a single by Tony Kubek.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Gil McDougald then doubled, plating Kubek all the way from first base.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Turley aided his own cause with an RBI single in the fourth, driving home Richardson, who had singled and moved to second on a passed ball.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Although Hoak doubled home Gino Cimoli in the bottom of the fourth to break the shutout, the Yankees extended their lead to 5–1 courtesy of a two-run home run by Mantle off Fred Green.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] In the sixth, the solid Yankee lead turned into a rout.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Elston Howard hit a lead-off triple and scored on Bobby Richardson's double to chase Green from the game.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] A passed ball by Smoky Burgess and error by shortstop Dick Groat on Tony Kubek's ground ball put runners on first and third with one out before McDougald's RBI single made it 7–1 Yankees.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] After a walk and strikeout, Yogi Berra's two-run single and Bill Skowron's RBI single made it 10–1 Yankees.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Red Witt relieved Labine and allowed back-to-back RBI singles to Howard and Richardson that made it 12–1 Yankees.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Mantle continued the onslaught by blasting a three-run home run in the seventh off Joe Gibbon and scoring on a wild pitch by Tom Cheney in the ninth after walking and moving to third on a double, making it 16–1 Yankees.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Although the Pirates tacked on two runs in the bottom half of the frame on back-to-back RBI singles by Gino Cimoli and Smoky Burgess, Bobby Shantz relieved Turley and got Don Hoak to hit into the game-ending double play.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] This decisive Yankee victory tied the series at a game apiece.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] For Game 3, the Series shifted to Yankee Stadium as Stengel sent Whitey Ford to the mound against Pittsburgh's Vinegar Bend Mizell.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Ford had somewhat of an off year (12–9, 3.08 ERA and 192.2 IP) for his lofty standards, but was brilliant against the Pirates.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] The Yankees continued the offensive onslaught they displayed in Game 2, grabbing a 6–0 lead by the end of the first inning.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] After two singles, Bill Skowron drove in the first run with an RBI single.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] After a walk loaded the bases, Elston Howard added another run with an RBI single off Clem Labine before Bobby Richardson capped the scoring with a grand slam (during the regular season, Richardson had hit only one home run, off Baltimore's Arnie Portocarrero on April 30).
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] The next time a first inning World Series Grand slam would be hit would be in the 2021 World Series, 61 years later.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] In the fourth, the Bronx Bombers added on four more runs, courtesy of a two-run home run by Mickey Mantle off Fred Green and—after three singles had loaded the bases—a two-run single by Richardson off Red Witt.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] The Pirates, meanwhile, could not get anything going against Ford, who tossed a masterful four-hitter.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] The Pirates had seen their pitching fail them in the last two games, as the team fell victim to the powerful Yankee bats.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] This was not the case in Game 4, however, as Pittsburgh sent Game 1 winner Vern Law to the hill against Ralph Terry.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] The game was scoreless until the bottom of the fourth, when Bill Skowron launched a home run off Law to give New York a 1–0 advantage.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] The very next half-inning, though, Pittsburgh stormed back, when with two on and two outs, Law doubled in Gino Cimoli to tie the game and Bill Virdon's two-run single put the Pirates up 3–1.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Law kept the potent pinstripers at bay, though the Yankees did scratch and claw for a single run in the bottom of the seventh when Skowron doubled, moved to third on a single by McDougald, and scored on a fielder's choice on a ball hit by Richardson.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] After a pinch-hit single by Johnny Blanchard, Pirate manager Danny Murtaugh brought in reliever Roy Face, who held the fort for the final 2+2⁄3 innings as Pittsburgh tied the series at two games apiece to ensure a return to Forbes Field.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] As it turned out, on this day Ditmar could not get out of the second inning once again.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Dick Stuart singled and was forced out at second on a fielder's choice hit by Gino Cimoli, who then moved to third on a double by Smoky Burgess.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Don Hoak then slapped a ground ball toward Yankee shortstop Tony Kubek, who flipped it to third baseman Gil McDougald in an attempt to retire Burgess, who was attempting to advance.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] However, McDougald dropped the ball for an error (Kubek's toss was accurate), allowing Cimoli to score, with Burgess safe at third, and Hoak reaching second on the error.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Bill Mazeroski then lashed a double to left, scoring Burgess and Hoak.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] After this offensive outburst, Stengel yanked Ditmar and replaced him with Luis Arroyo, who finally ended the inning and stranded Mazeroski.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] The next half-inning, New York picked up a run when Elston Howard doubled, moved to third on a ground-out by Bobby Richardson, and scored on another grounder by Kubek.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] However, the Pirates extended their lead back to three runs in the third, when Roberto Clemente singled home Groat, who led off with a double.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] In the bottom of the third, Roger Maris touched Haddix for a home run to deep right field.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Otherwise, however, the Pittsburgh hurler was in fine form, holding the Yankees at bay until the seventh, when he was replaced by Face.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] In the ninth, the Pirates added an insurance run off Ryne Duren.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Smoky Burgess had singled and taken second on an error; he was replaced at second by pinch-runner Joe Christopher, who moved to third on a wild pitch, and was singled in by Hoak.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Face then shut down the Yankees once again to give the Pirates a 5–2 victory and 3–2 series lead.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] For the sixth contest in Pittsburgh, the Yankees started Whitey Ford against the Pirates' Bob Friend.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] And as was the case the last time Ford had toed the rubber for the Yanks in Game 3, his teammates relentlessly mashed the ball, en route to a resounding 12–0 victory.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] In the top of the second, the Yankees went to work.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] After a Yogi Berra walk and a Bill Skowron single, Elston Howard was hit by a pitch to load the bases (Eli Grba ran for him).
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Ford himself then notched the first RBI of the game, with a ground ball single to his counterpart Friend that scored Berra.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] The next inning, after a lead-off hit-by-pitch and double, Mantle cracked a two-run single that scored Tony Kubek and Roger Maris.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] After a Yogi Berra single moved Mantle to third, Pirates skipper Danny Murtaugh removed the clearly ineffective Friend in favor of Tom Cheney.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Cheney, however, fared no better, as a Bill Skowron sacrifice fly scored Mantle and, after a single, a Richardson triple to deep left field scored Berra and Johnny Blanchard, making the score 6–0.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] The Yankees then ran away with the game, scoring two runs in each of the sixth, seventh, and eighth innings.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] In the sixth, Clete Boyer hit a lead-off triple off Fred Green and scored on Kubek's single.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] After another single, Berra's RBI single off Clem Labine made it 8–0 Yankees.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Next inning, after a lead-off double by Blanchard, Richardson ripped his second RBI triple of the contest, and Ford added his second RBI courtesy of a fielder's choice on a sacrifice bunt.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] In the eighth, Berra hit an RBI single with a runner on second, and later scored on Blanchard's double.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] As in Game 3, Ford was his masterful self, not letting the Pirates mount anything resembling a rally for the full nine innings.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] His second shutout of the series was critical, as it forced Game 7.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Yankee manager Casey Stengel would come under fire in Mickey Mantle's autobiography for letting Ford finish this game—instead of removing him once the Yankees had a comfortable lead—thus making him unavailable out of the bullpen if needed in Game 7.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] For the deciding seventh game, Bob Turley, the winning pitcher in Game 2, got the nod for the Yankees against the Pirates' Vern Law, the winning pitcher in Games 1 and 4.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Turley lasted only one inning plus one batter.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] After retiring the first two batters, Turley walked Bob Skinner, then first baseman Rocky Nelson homered, Pittsburgh's first home run since Bill Mazeroski's in Game 1, to give the Pirates a 2–0 lead.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Turley was then pulled after giving up a single to Smoky Burgess leading off the second.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Don Hoak then drew a walk against Bill Stafford, and a bunt single by Mazeroski loaded the bases.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Stafford appeared to get the Yankees out of trouble after inducing Law to hit into a double play, pitcher to catcher to first.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] But lead-off man Bill Virdon's single to right scored Hoak and Mazeroski and increased the Pirates' lead to 4–0.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] The Yankees got on the board in the fifth on Bill Skowron's lead-off home run, his second of the Series.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] In the sixth, Bobby Richardson led off with a single and Tony Kubek drew a walk.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Elroy Face relieved Law and got Roger Maris to pop out to Hoak in foul territory, but Mickey Mantle singled to score Richardson.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Face then blew the save when Yogi Berra followed with a three-run shot to right that gave the Yankees their first lead, 5–4.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] The Yankees extended their lead to 7–4 in the eighth with two more runs off Face.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] With two out, Berra walked, and Skowron singled when the Pirates couldn't get a force-out.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Johnny Blanchard (who had replaced Elston Howard at catcher for game 7) then singled to score Berra, and Clete Boyer doubled to score Skowron.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] But the Pirates retook the lead with a 5-run eighth inning.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Gino Cimoli (pinch-hitting for Face) led off with a single, and Virdon hit a ground ball to short for what could have been a double play.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] But the ball instead took a bad hop and hit Kubek in the throat, leaving everybody safe and knocking the wind out of Kubek.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] He eventually got up, and game footage showed him arguing with manager Stengel, seemingly insisting he was ok to stay in the game.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] He was eventually coaxed off the field and replaced.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] He was taken to a hospital and kept overnight for observation due to concerns surrounding his trachea swelling up and thus, causing difficulty breathing.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Back on the field, Dick Groat then chased Bobby Shantz (who had entered the game in the third and had pitched five innings, having not pitched more than four in any game during the regular season) with a single to score Cimoli and send Virdon to second.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Jim Coates relieved Shantz and got Skinner out on a sacrifice bunt, which moved the runners up.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Nelson followed with a fly ball to right, and Virdon declined to challenge Maris' throwing arm.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] The high chopper allowed Virdon to score, cutting the Yankee lead to 7–6.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Hal Smith, who had replaced Smoky Burgess at catcher after being pinch-run for by Joe Christopher followed with a three-run home run to give the Pirates a 9–7 lead.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Game 4 loser Ralph Terry relieved Coates and got the last out.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Bob Friend, an 18-game winner for the Pirates and their starter (and loser) in Games 2 and 6, came on in the ninth to try to protect the lead.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Bobby Richardson and pinch-hitter Dale Long both greeted him with singles, and Pirates manager Danny Murtaugh was forced to remove the veteran pitcher in favor of Harvey Haddix.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Although he got Roger Maris to foul out, Haddix gave up a key single to Mickey Mantle that scored Richardson and moved Long to third.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Yogi Berra followed, hitting a sharp grounder to first, with Rocky Nelson easily getting the second out.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Had Mantle been out on the play, the run would likely not have counted since the play happened so quickly that the runner on third might not have crossed the plate before the out was recorded.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] With Mantle safe, the inning continued, but ended when Bill Skowron hit into a force play.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Ralph Terry returned to the mound in the bottom of the ninth.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] The first batter to face him was Bill Mazeroski.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] As the Pirates erupted, the Yankees stood across the field in stunned disbelief.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] The improbable champions were outscored, out-hit, and outplayed, but somehow had managed to pull out a Game 7 victory.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Years later, Mickey Mantle was quoted in Ken Burns' documentary *Baseball* as saying that losing the 1960 series was the only loss, amateur or professional, he cried actual tears over.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] For Bill Mazeroski, by contrast, his Series-clinching home run was the highlight of a Hall of Fame career otherwise notable mostly for excellent defense.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Mazeroski became the first player to end the World Series with a home run.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Thirty-three years later, Joe Carter would become the only other player to end a World Series with a home run, doing so for the Toronto Blue Jays in the 1993 World Series against the Pirates' in-state rivals, the Philadelphia Phillies, albeit in Game 6.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Because of the game’s back-and-forth nature (especially in the eighth and ninth innings) and historic conclusion, the game is considered by some to be the greatest game in MLB history, as well as one of the greatest games in the history of professional sports.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Although most noted for the series-ending homer, Game 7 is also the only game in all of postseason history with no strikeouts recorded by either side.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Bobby Richardson of the Yankees was named MVP of the Series, the only time someone from the losing team has been so honored.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] He batted .367 with 12 RBIs and eight runs in the Series and hit the key grand slam in Game 3.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Prior to the mid-1970s, television networks and stations generally did not preserve their telecasts of sporting events, choosing instead to tape over them.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] As a result, the broadcasts of the first six games are no longer known to exist.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] The lone exception is a black-and-white kinescope of the entire telecast of Game 7, which was discovered in a wine cellar in Bing Crosby's former home in Hillsborough, California, in December 2009.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] A part-owner of the Pirates who was too superstitious to watch the Series live, Crosby listened to the decisive contest with his wife Kathryn and two friends on a shortwave radio in Paris, France.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Wanting to watch the game at a later date only if the Pirates won, he arranged for the telecast to be recorded by Ampex, in which he also held a financial investment.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] After viewing the kinescope, he placed it in his wine cellar, where it sat untouched for 49 years.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] It was finally found by Robert Bader, vice-president of marketing and production for Bing Crosby Enterprises, while looking through videotapes of Crosby's television specials which were to be transferred to DVD.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] The five-reel set is the only known complete copy of the historic game, which was originally broadcast in color.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] The NBC television announcers for the Series were Bob Prince and Mel Allen, the primary play-by-play voices for the Pirates and Yankees respectively.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Prince called the first half of Game 7 and conducted post-game interviews in the Pittsburgh clubhouse, while Allen did the latter portion of the game.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] On October 13, 2010, for the 50th anniversary of the series winning home run, a gala was hosted by the Byham Theater in downtown Pittsburgh, where the historic telecast of Game 7 was re-aired in its entirety.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] Bill Virdon, 1960 MVP Dick Groat and Yankee Bobby Richardson were guest speakers, with actor and Pittsburgh native Jeff Goldblum hosting the event.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] The MLB Network would air the game and gala on December 15, 2010.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] The telecast was also released on DVD by A&E Home Video.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] To date, the Pirates are the only team to win a seven-game postseason series while being out-scored by 28 runs or more.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] This would prove to be Casey Stengel's last World Series, as the Yankees soon sent him into retirement.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] This led to his famous remark, "I'll never make the mistake of turning 70 again." Mazeroski and Clemente were the last two remaining Pirates players from the 1960 World Series winners along with manager Danny Murtaugh and third-base coach Frank Oceak, when the Pirates won the World Series in 1971.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] To date, this is the last championship in any of the four major sports to be won in Pittsburgh by the home team, as the Pirates' two subsequent World Series championships in 1971 and 1979, both against the Baltimore Orioles, were clinched at Memorial Stadium.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] The Pittsburgh Penguins have won all five of their Stanley Cup titles on the road, and the Pittsburgh Steelers have won all six of their Super Bowl championships at neutral sites, as is customary in the NFL.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] The Yankees returned to the World Series the following year and the year after, and won back-to-back championships over the Cincinnati Reds and San Francisco Giants in five and seven games respectively.
[src:home-run/1960-world-series] In 2025, the NBC radio broadcast of Game 7 by Chuck Thompson was selected by the Library of Congress for preservation in the National Recording Registry.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] The **1976 National League Championship Series** was a postseason series in Major League Baseball’s 1976 postseason between the two division champions of the National League in the Cincinnati Reds and the Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] This was the eighth NLCS held in baseball history.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] For the fourth time in seven seasons, the Reds won the best-of-five series to reach the World Series.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] They did so in a three-game sweep, winning easily in the first two games before ending the series in their last at bat in Game 3.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] Reds starter Don Gullett held the Phils to two hits in eight strong innings, but allowed them to score first when Dave Cash hit a leadoff double, moved to third on a groundout and scored on Mike Schmidt's sacrifice fly.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] Gullett then walked three to load the bases, but got Tim McCarver to fly out to end the inning.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] The Reds tied the game in the third on Tony Perez's sacrifice fly off Steve Carlton, then took the lead in the sixth on George Foster's home run.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] After a double and error put two on, Gullett's RBI single made it 3–1 Reds.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] After allowing a leadoff double and walk in the eighth, Carlton was replaced by Tug McGraw, who allowed a one-out two-run double to Gullett and RBI double to Pete Rose.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] The Phillies attempted to rally in the ninth off Rawly Eastwick.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] Garry Maddox hit a leadoff single and scored on Greg Luzinski's double.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] After Dick Allen singled, Jay Johnstone's RBI single made it 6–3 Reds, but Eastwick retired the next two batters to end the game and give the Reds a 1–0 series lead.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] Buoyed by an RBI single by Bob Boone in the second after two leadoff singles and a homer by Greg Luzinski in the fifth off Pat Zachry, Phils starter Jim Lonborg no-hit the Reds until the sixth.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] After giving up a leadoff walk, one-out RBI single to Pete Rose, followed by another single by Ken Griffey, Lonborg was removed from the game by manager Danny Ozark.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] Gene Garber came in relief and after an intentional walk loaded the bases, two runs came across on an error by first baseman Dick Allen on a ball hit by Tony Pérez, then George Foster's RBI groundout made it 4–2 Reds.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] They added to their lead next inning on Griffey's RBI single off Tug McGraw and Perez's sacrifice fly off Ron Reed.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] Pedro Borbon pitched the last four innings to close to give the Reds a 2–0 series lead heading home.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] Once again, the Phillies got a strong starting pitching performance that went for naught.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] Jim Kaat held the Reds to one hit after six innings.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] Meanwhile, his teammates provided him a 3–0 lead via a consecutive doubles in the fourth by Mike Schmidt and Greg Luzinski off Gary Nolan and RBI doubles by Garry Maddox and Schmidt in the seventh after a leadoff walk off Manny Sarmiento.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] But in the bottom of the seventh, Kaat began to lose it.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] Ken Griffey led off with a single, Joe Morgan walked.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] Ron Reed then replaced Kaat to face Tony Pérez, who promptly singled home Griffey.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] George Foster followed with a sacrifice fly.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] After a walk to Johnny Bench, Reed retired Dave Concepción, but then surrendered a two-run triple to César Gerónimo to put the Reds ahead 4–3.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] In the eighth, the Phillies rallied against Reds closer Rawly Eastwick.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] Jay Johnstone led off with a double and went to third on a wild pitch as Bob Boone walked.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] Larry Bowa doubled in Johnstone and Dave Cash hit a sacrifice fly to give the Phillies the lead at 5–4.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] The Phillies added another run in the top of the ninth on an RBI triple by Johnstone to make it 6–4.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] With Reed still on the mound in the ninth, Foster and Bench hit back-to-back homers to tie the game.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] Gene Garber relieved and promptly gave up a single to Concepción.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] Tom Underwood came on to surrender a walk to Geronimo.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] Pinch-hitter Ed Armbrister sacrificed the runners to second and third.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] Underwood then intentionally walked Pete Rose to load the bases.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] With the infield drawn in, Griffey hit a high bouncer toward Bobby Tolan playing first.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] Tolan charged, but the ball got past him and Concepción scored to send the Reds to their second straight World Series; they would sweep the Yankees in four games, becoming the only team in the divisional era (to date) to go undefeated in the postseason.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] In the not to distant future, the Phillies would acquire Big Red Machine Reds' Pete Rose before the start of the 1979 season, and Tony Perez and Joe Morgan in the 1982–1983 off-season.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] By 1983, Rose was 42, Perez was 41, and Morgan was 39.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] Overall, the 1983 Phillies were one of the oldest teams ever assembled, being affectionately nicknamed "Wheeze Kids" due to the numerous veteran players on the team.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] The team started 43–42 before firing manager Pat Corrales.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] They finished 47–30 under Paul Owens and won a relatively weak National League East with just 90 wins.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] In the playoffs, they defeated the Los Angeles Dodgers in the National League Championship Series in four games, before losing the World Series to the Baltimore Orioles in five games.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] Despite the team's success, Rose and Morgan had near career-worst seasons.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] Morgan hit .230 in his lone season with the Phillies.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] The 42-year-old Rose batted only .245 with 121 hits and found himself benched during the latter part of the 1983 season when he appeared periodically to play and pinch hit.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] Rose did blossom as a pinch-hitter, with eight hits in 22 at-bats, a .364 average.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] Rose was even benched for game three of the World Series in Philadelphia, the first and only postseason game he did not start in his career.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] The Phillies later defeated the Reds in the 2010 National League Division Series.
[src:home-run/1976-national-league-championship-series] In Game 1 of the series, Roy Halladay pitched the second postseason no-hitter in MLB history.
[src:home-run/1990-in-baseball-p01] The following are the baseball events of the year 1990 throughout the world.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The **1993 World Series** was the championship series of Major League Baseball's (MLB) 1993 season.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The 90th edition of the World Series, it was a best-of-seven playoff played between the defending World Series champion and American League (AL) champion Toronto Blue Jays and the National League (NL) champion Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The Blue Jays defeated the Phillies in six games, becoming the seventh franchise in MLB history to win back-to-back championships.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] With Toronto ahead three games to two in the Series, but trailing Game 6 by a score of 6–5 in the bottom of the ninth inning, Joe Carter hit a game-winning three-run home run to clinch Toronto's second consecutive championship (the first team to repeat as champions since the 1977–78 Yankees).
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] This was only the second Series concluded by such a home run (the first was on a Bill Mazeroski home run for the Pittsburgh Pirates, in the bottom of the ninth in the seventh game of the 1960 World Series), and the first such occasion where a come-from-behind walk-off home run won a World Series.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] This victory was the last major North American professional sports championship won by a Canadian team until the Toronto Raptors won the 2019 NBA Finals.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] This was the fourth World Series with games played entirely on artificial turf, following the series of 1980, 1985, and 1987.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] A fifth occurred in 2020, although that was a neutral-site series during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The sixth would be the 2023 World Series.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Larry Andersen was the only member of the Phillies who had played for the team in its previous World Series appearance in 1983 (although he played for several other teams from 1986 to 1992).
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Darren Daulton had been a late season call-up in 1983, but only served as the bullpen catcher in the World Series that year.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] To date, this remains Toronto's last World Series victory, as well as the most recent championship in any of the four major leagues to be won by a Canadian team at their home venue.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The Jays would not return to the World Series until 32 years later, in 2025.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] They also did not return to the playoffs after 1993 until 2015.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Nick Leyva, who was fired as the Phillies manager 13 games into the 1991 season after going 4–9, and replaced by Jim Fregosi, was the 3B coach for the Blue Jays.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Leyva was the AAA Syracuse manager, but got the call up to the MLB staff after regular 3B coach Rich Hacker was badly injured in a car crash in July.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The Series' first game sent two staff aces—Curt Schilling for Philadelphia and Juan Guzman for Toronto—against one another.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The result was less than a pitcher's duel, however, as both teams scored early and often.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The Philles struck first in the top of the first on RBI singles by John Kruk and Darren Daulton aided by two walks.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] In the bottom of the second, after two singles and a wild pitch, Paul Molitor's single and Tony Fernandez's groundout scored a run each to tie the game.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The Phillies retook the lead in the fifth inning when Duncan tripled with one out and scored on a wild pitch, but White hit a home run to tie the game in the bottom of the inning.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The next inning, John Olerud hit a home run to put Toronto on top 5–4.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] In the seventh, after two one-out singles, Schilling was relieved by David West, who allowed an RBI double to White and two-run double to Roberto Alomar to pad Toronto's lead to 8–4.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The Phillies got a run in the ninth when Kruk hit a leadoff single, moved to second on an error and scored on Jim Eisenreich's two-out single, but Duane Ward got Ricky Jordan to fly out to end the game as Toronto won 8–5.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Al Leiter pitched 2+2⁄3 innings—in relief of an erratic Juan Guzman, who walked four in just five innings—for his first World Series win.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Alomar made an amazing diving catch on a Lenny Dykstra looper behind first in the top of the fifth.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] In the second game of the Series, ALCS MVP Dave Stewart was on the mound for Toronto and Terry Mulholland started for Philadelphia.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Philadelphia jumped out to an early lead: in the third inning, After two walks, John Kruk and Dave Hollins hit back-to-back RBI singles, then Jim Eisenreich followed with a three-run home run to deep right-center to put them up 5–0.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Toronto cut the lead to 6–4 in the eighth when Paul Molitor hit a leadoff double off Roger Mason, stole third and scored on John Olerud's sacrifice fly off Mitch Williams.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Alomar then walked and stole second, but was caught stealing third to end the inning.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Williams then pitched a scoreless ninth as the Phillies won to tie the series.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Mulholland pitched 5+2⁄3 innings, allowing three earned runs, for the win.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The West Chester University "Incomparable" Golden Rams Marching Band performed the pregame show for Game 3.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] As he had in the preceding World Series, when the 1993 edition moved into the National League ballpark Toronto manager Cito Gaston was faced with a decision regarding his designated hitter.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Against a left-handed pitcher, Gaston decided to stick with the right-handed veteran Molitor, but had left-hitting Olerud on the bench if needed later in the game.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The Blue Jays sent future Cy Young winner Pat Hentgen to the mound for Game 3.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The Phillies countered with veteran Danny Jackson, who was one of the few Phillies that had pitched in a World Series; he was part of the 1985 Kansas City and 1990 Cincinnati teams that won World Series championships.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The Blue Jays struck for two runs before recording an out.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] After Rickey Henderson’s leadoff single and Devon White’s walk, Molitor tripled to drive them both in.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Joe Carter then extended the Toronto lead to 3–0 with a sacrifice fly, but Jackson got out of the inning by retiring Roberto Alomar and Tony Fernandez.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The Phillies got two runners in scoring position with one out in their half of the first, with Mariano Duncan and John Kruk singling and an error by Carter enabling both runners to advance a base.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Hentgen ended the threat by striking out Dave Hollins and Darren Daulton; the Phillies only got one more man on base before the sixth inning.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Molitor struck again with two out in the fourth, hitting a solo home run to extend the lead to four.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Carter, Alomar, and Fernandez followed with singles to load the bases, but Jackson struck out Ed Sprague Jr. to end the inning without further damage.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Jackson would be lifted for a pinch hitter in the fifth.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] In the sixth, Phillies reliever Ben Rivera gave up a leadoff single to Alomar.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] With Fernandez up, the speedy second baseman stole second and third and scored on a sacrifice fly by his double-play partner.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The Phillies got on the board in the bottom of the inning on a single by Jim Eisenreich that drove in Kruk.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] This was Hentgen’s last inning of work; Danny Cox would come on for the seventh.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] In the top of the seventh, Henderson hit a leadoff double, then scored on a triple by White.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] After a walk by Molitor and a Carter strikeout, Alomar's RBI single made it 7–1 in favor of Toronto.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Bobby Thigpen relieved Rivera and walked Fernandez before Sprague's sacrifice fly made it 8–1.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The Phillies managed a run off Cox in the seventh, with a string of singles by Milt Thompson, Lenny Dykstra, and Duncan with one out resulting in Thompson scoring.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The Blue Jays finished their offensive output in the top of the ninth with an RBI triple by Alomar that scored Molitor and a single by Fernandez that followed to bring in Alomar.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Thompson hit a solo home run against Toronto closer Duane Ward in the bottom of the ninth to finish out the scoring, and the Blue Jays emerged with a 10–3 victory and a two-games-to-one lead in the series.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] In the fourth game of the Series, Toronto sent Todd Stottlemyre to the mound while Philadelphia countered with Tommy Greene.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] It had been a rainy day in Philadelphia, which water-logged the aging turf at Veterans Stadium, making for particularly slippery conditions.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Toronto loaded the bases in the first on a double, walk and single.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Paul Molitor walked to force in a run before Tony Fernandez's single scored two more.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] In the bottom half, three walks loaded the bases for the Phillies before Jim Eisenreich walked to force in a run, then Milt Thompson's three-run triple put the Phillies up 4–3.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Lenny Dykstra's two-run home run next inning made it 6–3 Phillies.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] In the top of the third, after a one-out walk and single, consecutive RBI singles by Tony Fernandez and Pat Borders cut the lead to 6–5.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Roger Mason relieved Greene and after a groundout and walk, Devon White's two-run single put Toronto up 7–6, but the Phillies tied the game in the fourth when Dykstra doubled with two outs off Al Leiter and scored on Mariano Duncan's single.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Next inning, after a leadoff single, Darren Daulton's two-run home run put the Phillies up 9–7.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] After another single, Thompson's RBI double made it 10–7, then Dykstra's second home run of the game made it 12–7 Phillies.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] In the sixth, White hit a leadoff double before scoring on Roberto Alomar's single off David West.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] After a single and hit-by-pitch loaded the bases, Fernandez's RBI groundout cut the Phillies' lead to 12–9, but they added a run in the bottom half when Dave Hollins hit a leadoff double off Tony Castillo and scored on Thompson's two-out single.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Next inning, a hit-by-pitch to Daulton with the bases loaded made it 14–9 Phillies.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] In the eighth, though, after a one-out single and walk off Larry Andersen, Molitor's RBI double made it 14–10 Phillies.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Fernandez then hit an RBI single off Mitch Williams.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] A walk loaded the bases, then after a strikeout, Rickey Henderson's single and White's triple scored two runs each to put Toronto ahead 15–14.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Duane Ward earned the save, retiring the last four Phillies batters.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Three new World Series records were set, including the longest game (4:14), most total runs scored in a single game (29), and most runs scored by a losing team (14).
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Also, Charlie Williams became the first African American to serve as the home plate umpire for a World Series game.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Two death threats directed towards Mitch Williams were phoned into Veterans Stadium as soon as it became evident that Williams was going to be the losing pitcher of Game 4.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Williams was not aware of the death threats until after Game 5.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The offenses were due for an off-day, and it came in Game 5 courtesy of a Curt Schilling (Philadelphia) and Juan Guzman (Toronto) pitching duel.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] With the Phillies' backs to the wall, Schilling shut down the previously unstoppable Toronto offense, limiting the team to just five hits, three walks, no extra-base hits (although catcher Pat Borders had two hits) and no runs in a complete-game shutout.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] It was only the second time all season that Toronto had been shut out.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Guzman pitched well in a losing effort, allowing only two runs and five hits in seven innings of work.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The two runs scored as a result of scrappy baserunning play from the Philadelphia offense.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] In the first inning, Lenny Dykstra walked, stole second, moved to third on a Pat Borders throwing error during the steal, and scored on a John Kruk ground out.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] In the second inning, Darren Daulton opened with a double, took third on a groundout, and scored on a Kevin Stocker single.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] As it turned out, it was the final postseason baseball game in Veterans Stadium.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] It was demolished after the 2003 season.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The sixth game in the Series was a rematch between Game 2 starters Terry Mulholland and Dave Stewart, who would have similar results.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Toronto scored in the bottom of the first with a run-scoring Paul Molitor triple after a walk, Joe Carter sacrifice fly to score Molitor, and Roberto Alomar RBI single after a double.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The Phillies got on the board in the fourth when Darren Daulton doubled with two outs and scored on Jim Eisenreich's single, but the Blue Jays got that run back in the bottom of the inning when Alomar hit a leadoff double, moved to third on a groundout and scored on Ed Sprague Jr.'s sacrifice fly.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Paul Molitor added a home run in the fifth inning while the Toronto fans were chanting "MVP" for Paul, bringing the score to 5–1 for Toronto.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Molitor became the first player in World Series history to have at least two home runs, two doubles, and two triples.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] In the seventh inning, Philadelphia fought back with five runs.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] After a walk and single, Lenny Dykstra hit a three-run home run to knock Stewart out of the game.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Mariano Duncan singled off reliever Danny Cox, stole second, and scored on Dave Hollins's RBI single to tie the game.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] A walk and single loaded the bases before Pete Incaviglia hit a sacrifice fly to put the Phillies up 6–5.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The Blue Jays would try to threaten in the bottom of the eighth.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] John Olerud drew a one-out walk and the Phillies brought in Larry Andersen to face Roberto Alomar.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] After Alomar grounded out, Andersen then hit Tony Fernandez with a pitch and walked Ed Sprague Jr. to load the bases.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Andersen got out of the inning by inducing a pop-fly to Pat Borders.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] This became significant in the next inning, with the batting order reset to the top with Rickey Henderson leading off.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Philadelphia closer Mitch Williams came on to pitch the bottom of the ninth with his team clinging to a 6–5 lead.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] After beginning the inning by walking Rickey Henderson, Williams tried to counter Henderson's speed by using a slide-step style of pitching delivery.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Prior to the game, Williams had never used the slide-step delivery in his career, and this may have cut back on his velocity.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The walk to Henderson was followed by a Devon White flyout and a Paul Molitor single that moved Henderson to second.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Joe Carter came up next and, with the count 2–2, he hit a three-run home run to win the game and the World Series.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Just before the fifth and final pitch to Joe Carter, CBS Sports announcer Tim McCarver commented that Carter (relatively unproductive in the Series to date) looked awkward and uncomfortable at the plate.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The same pitch allowed Blue Jays radio announcer Tom Cheek the opportunity to utter his famous "Touch 'em all, Joe" quote, when Joe Carter clinched the series.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Carter joined Bill Mazeroski as the only two players to win a World Series with a home run in the bottom of the ninth inning (Mazeroski hit his home run in the deciding Game 7, while Carter hit his in Game 6).
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Carter was actively involved in the final play of the World Series for the second year in a row.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] In the previous year, Carter caught the final out as first baseman after relief pitcher Mike Timlin fielded Otis Nixon's bunt.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Taking the 1993 ALCS into account (where he caught the final out in the outfield), he had been involved in the final play of three straight postseason championship series.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] American League president Bobby Brown presented the World Series Trophy instead of the Commissioner of Baseball; this event also occurred in the year before.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The Blue Jays became the second expansion team to win two World Series championships, following the New York Mets in 1986.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] This has since been achieved by the Florida Marlins in 2003, the Kansas City Royals in 2015, and the Houston Astros in 2022.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] With the Montreal Canadiens winning the 1993 Stanley Cup Final five months earlier, it marked the only time Canadian teams won multiple league championships among the four major North American team sports in a calendar year.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] —Mitch Williams on his feelings about surrendering the home run to Joe Carter.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Roger Angell's review of the World Series in *The New Yorker* was entitled "Oh, What a Lovely War".
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] When Joe Carter appeared in the 1996 All-Star Game at Veterans Stadium, he was booed by the crowd for his aforementioned home run that won him this World Series.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Both teams would experience absences from the postseason; the Phillies did not return to the postseason until 2007, or appear in another World Series until their championship season of 2008, bringing the city of Philadelphia its first championship since the 76ers swept the 1983 NBA Finals.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The general manager of the Blue Jays, Pat Gillick, was general manager of the Phillies team that won the 2008 World Series.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The Blue Jays did not qualify for the playoffs again until the 2015 season.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] This was the last time a Toronto team made it to the championship round in one of the four major sports until the Toronto Raptors in their 2019 championship season.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The Blue Jays would not return to the World Series until 2025, when they ultimately lost to the Los Angeles Dodgers in a seven-game thriller.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] By accumulating 45 runs over the course of the series, the Blue Jays scored the highest number of runs of *any* series-winning team in World Series history.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Only the series-losing 1960 New York Yankees accumulated more runs in a series (55).
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Coincidentally, that series also ended on a walk-off home run.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] 1993 was the last postseason played under a two-division, two post-season round format.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] After the season, MLB owners agreed to a new three-division setup, with extra post-season round (League Division Series).
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The extra round format had been used once before during the 1981 strike shortened season.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] CBS Sports covered the World Series on television for the fourth consecutive year; it was also the final World Series in CBS's contract to air Major League Baseball games.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] For the second consecutive year, Sean McDonough served as lead announcer, with Tim McCarver serving as analyst for the fourth consecutive year.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Pregame and postgame shows saw Andrea Joyce and Pat O'Brien as hosts, while Lesley Visser and Jim Gray were field level reporters.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] CBS Radio was once again the nationwide radio partner (in the US) for the World Series.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Vin Scully led the broadcast for a fourth consecutive year, with Johnny Bench serving as analyst for the fifth and last time.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] John Rooney served as the pregame and postgame show host.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The game was heard on radio throughout Canada on a series of stations picking up the feed of CJCL-AM in Toronto, with the game being called by Jerry Howarth and Tom Cheek.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Cheek's famous call of the Carter home run ("Touch 'em all Joe, you'll never hit a bigger home run in your life!") lives on in Blue Jays folklore.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Tom Cheek never called another postseason game in his role as voice of the Blue Jays, from which he retired in 2005 prior to his death from brain cancer.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Locally in Philadelphia, the World Series was called on WOGL-AM by Harry Kalas, Richie Ashburn, Chris Wheeler, Andy Musser, and Garry Maddox.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The 1993 series was Richie Ashburn's last as a Phillies broadcaster, as he died in 1997.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Andy Musser also called his last World Series as a member of the Phillies' broadcast team; he retired in 2001 and died eleven years later.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Game 6 also marked Johnny Bench's final broadcast for CBS Radio after nine years (he would be replaced on CBS Radio's World Series broadcasts by Jeff Torborg), while Harry Kalas would not call another World Series until 2008.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Kalas later died in 2009 prior to a game at Nationals Park in Washington, D.C.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Chris Wheeler continued to call games for the Phillies until being released in 2014 and Jerry Howarth continued to call Blue Jays games, moving into the primary play-by-play position following the death of Cheek, until his retirement before the 2018 season.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Howarth would return to call postseason games when the Blue Jays qualified in 2015 and 2016, where they were eliminated in the ALCS both years.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Fastball, it's hit to left field, down the line, in the corner, home run!
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Joe Carter, who took the 2 and 0 pitch for a strike right down the middle, hits the 2 and 1 (sic) pitch over the left field wall and the Toronto Blue Jays come back with 3 in the bottom of the ninth inning to become the World Champions yet again.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The final score: Toronto 8, Philadelphia 6.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Trying to lay off that ball, low to the outside part of the plate, he just went after one.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Here's a pitch on the way, a swing and a belt, left field, way back...
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The Blue Jays are World Series champions, as Joe Carter hits a three-run home run in the ninth inning and the Blue Jays have repeated as World Series champions!
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] You'll never hit a bigger home run in your life!
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The 2–2 pitch, line drive in deep left, this ball is outta here.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Three-run home run, Joe Carter, and the Toronto Blue Jays are the world champions of baseball for the second straight year.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] A three-run home run in the bottom of the ninth by Joe Carter who's being mobbed at home plate.
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Well-hit down the left-field line, way back and GONE!
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The winners and still world champions, the Toronto Blue Jays!
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] Toronto rapper Choclair refers to Joe Carter's walk-off home run in his 1999 song, "Let's Ride".
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] On July 29, 2015, Toronto rapper Drake released a diss track against Philadelphia rapper Meek Mill entitled "Back to Back".
[src:home-run/1993-world-series] The cover of the diss track features a picture of Joe Carter, just after hitting the series-clinching home run.
[src:home-run/home-run] In baseball, a **home run** (abbreviated **HR**) is scored when the ball is hit in such a way that the batter is able to circle the bases and reach home plate safely in one play without any errors being committed by the defensive team.
[src:home-run/home-run] A home run is usually achieved by hitting the ball over the outfield fence between the foul poles (or hitting either foul pole) without the ball touching the field.
[src:home-run/home-run] Inside-the-park home runs, when the batter reaches home safely while the baseball is in play on the field, are infrequent.
[src:home-run/home-run] In very rare cases, a fielder attempting to catch a ball in flight may misplay it and knock it over the outfield fence, resulting in a home run.
[src:home-run/home-run] An official scorer will credit the batter with a hit, a run scored, and a run batted in (RBI), as well as an RBI for each runner on base.
[src:home-run/home-run] The pitcher is recorded as having given up a hit and a run, with additional runs charged for each base-runner that scores.
[src:home-run/home-run] Nicknames for a home run include "homer", "round-tripper", "four-bagger", "big fly", "goner" "dinger", "long ball", "jack", "quadruple", "moon shot", "bomb", "tater", and "blast", while a player hitting a home run may be said to have "gone deep" or "gone yard".
[src:home-run/home-run] A home run is most often scored when the ball is hit over the outfield wall between the foul poles (in fair territory) before it touches the ground (in flight), and without being caught or deflected back onto the field by a fielder.
[src:home-run/home-run] A batted ball is also a home run if it touches either a foul pole or its attached screen before touching the ground, as the foul poles are by definition in fair territory.
[src:home-run/home-run] Additionally, many major-league ballparks have ground rules stating that a batted ball in flight that strikes a specified location or fixed object is a home run; this usually applies to objects that are beyond the outfield wall but are located such that it may be difficult for the umpire to judge.
[src:home-run/home-run] In professional baseball, a batted ball that goes over the outfield wall *after* touching the ground (i.e. a ball that bounces over the outfield wall) becomes an automatic double.
[src:home-run/home-run] This is colloquially referred to as a "ground rule double" even though it is uniform across all of Major League Baseball, per MLB rules 5.05(a)(6) through 5.05(a)(9).
[src:home-run/home-run] A fielder is allowed to reach over the wall to try to catch the ball as long as his feet are on or over the field during the attempt, and if the fielder successfully catches the ball while it is in flight the batter is out, even if the ball had already passed the vertical plane of the wall.
[src:home-run/home-run] However, since the fielder is not part of the field, a ball that bounces off a fielder (including his glove) and over the wall without touching the ground is still a home run.
[src:home-run/home-run] A home run accomplished in any of the above manners is an automatic home run.
[src:home-run/home-run] The ball is dead, even if it rebounds back onto the field (e.g., from striking a foul pole), and the batter and any preceding runners cannot be put out at any time while running the bases.
[src:home-run/home-run] This stipulation is in Approved Ruling (2) of Rule 7.10(b).
[src:home-run/home-run] An inside-the-park home run is a rare play in which a batter rounds all four bases for a home run without the baseball leaving the field of play.
[src:home-run/home-run] Unlike with an outside-the-park home run, the batter-runner and all preceding runners are liable to be put out by the defensive team at any time while running the bases.
[src:home-run/home-run] This can only happen if the ball does not leave the ballfield.
[src:home-run/home-run] In the early days of baseball, outfields were much more spacious, reducing the likelihood of an over-the-fence home run, while increasing the likelihood of an inside-the-park home run, as a ball getting past an outfielder had more distance that it could roll before a fielder could track it down.
[src:home-run/home-run] Modern outfields are much less spacious and more uniformly designed than in the game's early days.
[src:home-run/home-run] Therefore, inside-the-park home runs are now rare.
[src:home-run/home-run] The speed of the runner is crucial as even triples are relatively rare in most modern ballparks.
[src:home-run/home-run] If any defensive play on an inside-the-park home run is labeled an error by the official scorer, a home run is not scored.
[src:home-run/home-run] Instead, it is scored as a single, double, triple, or even not a hit.
[src:home-run/home-run] The batter-runner and any applicable preceding runners are said to have taken all additional bases on error.
[src:home-run/home-run] All runs scored on such a play, however, still count.
[src:home-run/home-run] An example of an unexpected bounce occurred during the 2007 Major League Baseball All-Star Game at AT&T Park in San Francisco on July 10, 2007.
[src:home-run/home-run] Ichiro Suzuki of the American League team hit a fly ball that caromed off the right-center field wall in the opposite direction from where National League right fielder Ken Griffey Jr. was expecting it to go.
[src:home-run/home-run] By the time the ball was relayed, Ichiro had already crossed the plate standing up.
[src:home-run/home-run] This was the first inside-the-park home run in All-Star Game history and led to Suzuki being named the game's Most Valuable Player.
[src:home-run/home-run] Home runs are often characterized by the number of runners on base at the time.
[src:home-run/home-run] A home run hit with the bases empty is never called a "one-run homer", but rather a **solo home run**, **solo homer**, or "solo shot".
[src:home-run/home-run] With one runner on base, two runs score (the base-runner and the batter), and thus the home run is often called a **two-run homer** or **two-run shot**.
[src:home-run/home-run] Similarly, a home run with two runners on base is a **three-run homer** or **three-run shot**.
[src:home-run/home-run] The term "four-run homer" is never used.
[src:home-run/home-run] Hitting a grand slam is the best possible result for the batter's turn at bat and the worst possible result for the pitcher and his team.
[src:home-run/home-run] A grand slam occurs when the bases are "loaded" (that is, base runners are at first, second, and third base) and the batter hits a home run.
[src:home-run/home-run] According to *The Dickson Baseball Dictionary*, the term originated in the card game of contract bridge.
[src:home-run/home-run] An **inside-the-park grand slam** is a grand slam that is also an inside-the-park home run, a home run without the ball leaving the field, and it is very rare, due to the relative rarity of loading the bases along with the significant rarity (nowadays) of inside-the-park home runs.
[src:home-run/home-run] On July 25, 1956, Roberto Clemente became the only MLB player to have ever scored a walk-off inside-the-park grand slam in a 9–8 Pittsburgh Pirates win over the Chicago Cubs, at Forbes Field.
[src:home-run/home-run] On April 23, 1999, Fernando Tatís Sr. made history by hitting two grand slams in one inning, both against Chan Ho Park of the Los Angeles Dodgers.
[src:home-run/home-run] With this feat, Tatís also set a Major League record with 8 RBI in one inning.
[src:home-run/home-run] On July 29, 2003, against the Texas Rangers, Bill Mueller of the Boston Red Sox became the only player in major league history to hit two grand slams in one game from opposite sides of the plate; he hit three home runs in that game, and his two grand slams were in consecutive at-bats.
[src:home-run/home-run] On August 25, 2011, the New York Yankees became the first team to hit three grand slams in one game vs the Oakland A's.
[src:home-run/home-run] The Yankees eventually won the game 22–9, after trailing 7–1.
[src:home-run/home-run] On October 25, 2024, Freddie Freeman made history by hitting a walk-off grand slam in the bottom of the 10th inning in Game 1 of the World Series, leading the Los Angeles Dodgers to a 6-3 victory over the New York Yankees.
[src:home-run/home-run] Freeman is the only player in MLB history to do so in the World Series.
[src:home-run/home-run] These types of home runs are characterized by the specific game situation in which they occur, and can theoretically occur on either an outside-the-park or inside-the-park home run.
[src:home-run/home-run] A walk-off home run is a home run hit by the home team in the bottom of the ninth inning, any extra inning, or other scheduled final inning, which gives the home team the lead and thereby ends the game.
[src:home-run/home-run] The term is attributed to Hall of Fame relief pitcher Dennis Eckersley, so named because after the run is scored, the losing team has to "walk off" the field.
[src:home-run/home-run] Two World Series have ended via the "walk-off" home run.
[src:home-run/home-run] The first was the 1960 World Series when Bill Mazeroski of the Pittsburgh Pirates hit a ninth-inning solo home run in the seventh game of the series off New York Yankees pitcher Ralph Terry to give the Pirates the World Championship.
[src:home-run/home-run] The second time was the 1993 World Series when Joe Carter of the Toronto Blue Jays hit a ninth-inning three-run home run off Philadelphia Phillies pitcher Mitch Williams in Game 6 of the series, to help the Toronto Blue Jays capture their second World Series Championship in a row.
[src:home-run/home-run] Such a home run can also be called a "sudden death" or "sudden victory" home run.
[src:home-run/home-run] That usage has lessened as "walk-off home run" has gained favor.
[src:home-run/home-run] A walk-off home run over the fence is an exception to baseball's one-run rule.
[src:home-run/home-run] Normally if the home team is tied or behind in the ninth or extra innings, the game ends as soon as the home team scores enough runs to achieve a lead.
[src:home-run/home-run] If the home team has two outs in the inning, and the game is tied, the game will officially end either the moment the batter successfully reaches first base or the moment the runner touches home plate—whichever happens last.
[src:home-run/home-run] However, this is superseded by the "ground rule", which provides automatic doubles (when a ball-in-play hits the ground first and then leaves the playing field) and home runs (when a ball-in-play leaves the playing field without ever touching the ground).
[src:home-run/home-run] In the latter case, all base runners including the batter are allowed to cross the plate.
[src:home-run/home-run] A leadoff home run is a home run hit by the first batter of a team, the leadoff hitter of the first inning of the game.
[src:home-run/home-run] In MLB (major league Baseball), Rickey Henderson holds the career record with 81 lead-off home runs.
[src:home-run/home-run] Craig Biggio holds the National League career record with 53, fourth overall following Henderson, George Springer with 61, and Alfonso Soriano with 54.
[src:home-run/home-run] As of August 26, 2025, Springer holds the career record among active players, with 61 leadoff home runs, which also ranks second all-time.
[src:home-run/home-run] In 1996, Brady Anderson set a Major League record by hitting a lead-off home run in four consecutive games.
[src:home-run/home-run] When consecutive batters hit home runs, it's referred to as back-to-back home runs.
[src:home-run/home-run] The home runs are still considered back-to-back even if the batters hit their home runs off different pitchers.
[src:home-run/home-run] A third batter hitting a home run is commonly referred to as back-to-back-to-back.
[src:home-run/home-run] Four home runs in a row have only occurred eleven times in Major League Baseball history.
[src:home-run/home-run] Following convention, this is called back-to-back-to-back-to-back.
[src:home-run/home-run] The most recent occurrence was on July 2, 2022, when the St.
[src:home-run/home-run] Louis Cardinals hit four in a row against the Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:home-run/home-run] Nolan Arenado, Nolan Gorman, Juan Yepez, and Dylan Carlson hit consecutive home runs during the first inning off starting pitcher Kyle Gibson.
[src:home-run/home-run] On June 9, 2019, the Washington Nationals hit four in a row against the San Diego Padres in Petco Park as Howie Kendrick, Trea Turner, Adam Eaton and Anthony Rendon homered off pitcher Craig Stammen.
[src:home-run/home-run] Stammen became the fifth pitcher to surrender back-to-back-to-back-to-back home runs, following Paul Foytack on July 31, 1963, Chase Wright on April 22, 2007, Dave Bush on August 10, 2010, and Michael Blazek on July 27, 2017.
[src:home-run/home-run] On August 14, 2008, the Chicago White Sox defeated the Kansas City Royals 9–2.
[src:home-run/home-run] In this game, Jim Thome, Paul Konerko, Alexei Ramírez, and Juan Uribe hit back-to-back-to-back-to-back home runs in that order.
[src:home-run/home-run] Thome, Konerko, and Ramirez hit their home runs against Joel Peralta, while Uribe did it off Rob Tejeda.
[src:home-run/home-run] On April 22, 2007, the Boston Red Sox were trailing the New York Yankees 3–0 when Manny Ramirez, J.
[src:home-run/home-run] Drew, Mike Lowell and Jason Varitek hit consecutive home runs to put them up 4–3.
[src:home-run/home-run] They eventually went on to win the game 7–6 after a three-run home run by Mike Lowell in the bottom of the seventh inning.
[src:home-run/home-run] On September 18, 2006, trailing 9–5 to the San Diego Padres in the ninth inning, Jeff Kent, J.
[src:home-run/home-run] Drew, Russell Martin, and Marlon Anderson of the Los Angeles Dodgers hit back-to-back-to-back-to-back home runs to tie the game.
[src:home-run/home-run] After giving up a run in the top of the tenth, the Dodgers won the game in the bottom of the tenth, on a walk-off two-run home run by Nomar Garciaparra.
[src:home-run/home-run] Drew has been part of two different sets of back-to-back-to-back-to-back home runs.
[src:home-run/home-run] In both occurrences, his home run was the second of the four.
[src:home-run/home-run] On September 30, 1997, in the sixth inning of Game One of the American League Division Series between the New York Yankees and Cleveland Indians, Tim Raines, Derek Jeter and Paul O'Neill hit back-to-back-to-back home runs for the Yankees.
[src:home-run/home-run] This was the first occurrence of three home runs in a row ever in postseason play.
[src:home-run/home-run] The Boston Red Sox repeated the feat in Game Four of the 2007 American League Championship Series, also against the Indians.
[src:home-run/home-run] The Indians returned the favor in Game One of the 2016 American League Division Series.
[src:home-run/home-run] Twice in MLB history, two brothers have hit back-to-back home runs.
[src:home-run/home-run] On April 23, 2013, brothers Melvin Upton Jr.
[src:home-run/home-run] Upton) and Justin Upton hit back-to-back home runs.
[src:home-run/home-run] The first time was on September 15, 1938, when Lloyd Waner and Paul Waner performed the feat.
[src:home-run/home-run] Simple back-to-back home runs are a relatively frequent occurrence.
[src:home-run/home-run] If a pitcher gives up a home run, he might have his concentration broken and might alter his normal approach in an attempt to "make up for it" by striking out the next batter with some fastballs.
[src:home-run/home-run] Sometimes the next batter will be expecting that and will capitalize on it.
[src:home-run/home-run] A notable back-to-back home run of that type in World Series play involved "Babe Ruth's called shot" in 1932, which was accompanied by various Ruthian theatrics, yet the pitcher, Charlie Root, was allowed to stay in the game.
[src:home-run/home-run] He delivered just one more pitch, which Lou Gehrig drilled out of the park for a back-to-back shot, after which Root was removed from the game.
[src:home-run/home-run] In Game 3 of the 1976 NLCS, George Foster and Johnny Bench hit back-to-back home runs in the last of the ninth off Ron Reed to tie the game.
[src:home-run/home-run] The Series-winning run was scored later in the inning.
[src:home-run/home-run] Another notable pair of back-to-back home runs occurred on September 14, 1990, when Ken Griffey Sr. and Ken Griffey Jr. hit back-to-back home runs, off Kirk McCaskill, the only father-and-son duo to do so in Major League history.
[src:home-run/home-run] On May 2, 2002, Bret Boone and Mike Cameron of the Seattle Mariners hit back-to-back home runs off starter Jon Rauch in the first inning of a game against the Chicago White Sox.
[src:home-run/home-run] The Mariners batted around in the inning, and Boone and Cameron came up to bat against reliever Jim Parque with two outs, again hitting back-to-back home runs and becoming the only pair of teammates to hit back-to-back home runs twice in the same inning.
[src:home-run/home-run] On June 19, 2012, José Bautista and Colby Rasmus hit back-to-back home runs and back-to-back-to-back home runs with Edwin Encarnación for a lead change in each instance.
[src:home-run/home-run] On July 23, 2017, Whit Merrifield, Jorge Bonifacio, and Eric Hosmer of the Kansas City Royals hit back-to-back-to-back home runs in the fourth inning against the Chicago White Sox.
[src:home-run/home-run] On June 20, 2018, George Springer, Alex Bregman, and Jose Altuve of the Houston Astros hit back-to-back-to-back home runs in the sixth inning against the Tampa Bay Rays.
[src:home-run/home-run] Louis Cardinals began the game against the Milwaukee Brewers with back-to-back home runs from Dexter Fowler and Tommy Pham.
[src:home-run/home-run] Then in the bottom of the ninth, with two outs and the Cardinals leading 4–3, Christian Yelich homered to tie the game; and Ryan Braun hit the next pitch for a walk-off home run.
[src:home-run/home-run] This is the only major league game to begin and end with back-to-back home runs.
[src:home-run/home-run] On May 5, 2019, Eugenio Suarez, Jesse Winker and Derek Dietrich of the Cincinnati Reds, hit back-to-back-to-back home runs on three straight pitches against Jeff Samardzija of the San Francisco Giants in the bottom of the first inning.
[src:home-run/home-run] On October 30, 2021, Dansby Swanson and Jorge Soler hit back-to-back home runs for the Atlanta Braves off Houston Astros pitcher Cristian Javier to give the Braves a 3–2 lead in the bottom of the seventh in Game 4 of the World Series.
[src:home-run/home-run] On October 18, 2024, Aaron Judge and Giancarlo Stanton hit back-to-back quadruples to take the lead in a game of the American League Championship Series.
[src:home-run/home-run] On March 29, 2025, New York Yankees batters Paul Goldschmidt, Cody Bellinger, and Aaron Judge became the first trio to hit back-to-back-to-back home runs on the first three pitches of a game.
[src:home-run/home-run] They accomplished this feat against Milwaukee Brewers pitcher Nestor Cortes.
[src:home-run/home-run] On April 29, 2025, New York Yankees batters Trent Grisham, Aaron Judge, and Ben Rice hit back-to-back-to-back home runs in the top of the first inning off Baltimore Orioles pitcher Kyle Gibson.
[src:home-run/home-run] The Yankees became the first team to hit three consecutive homers to start a game twice in one season.
[src:home-run/home-run] The record for consecutive home runs by a batter under any circumstances is four.
[src:home-run/home-run] Of the sixteen players (through 2012) who have hit four in one game, six have hit them consecutively.
[src:home-run/home-run] Twenty-eight other batters have hit four consecutive across two games.
[src:home-run/home-run] Bases on balls do not count as at-bats, and Ted Williams holds the record for consecutive home runs across the most games, four in four games played, during September 17–22, 1957, for the Red Sox.
[src:home-run/home-run] Williams hit a pinch-hit home run on the 17th; walked as a pinch-hitter on the 18th; there was no game on the 19th; hit another pinch-homer on the 20th; homered and then was lifted for a pinch-runner after at least one walk, on the 21st; and homered after at least one walk on the 22nd.
[src:home-run/home-run] All in all, he had four walks interspersed among his four homers.
[src:home-run/home-run] In World Series play, Reggie Jackson hit a record three in one Series game, the final game (Game 6) in 1977.
[src:home-run/home-run] But those three were a part of a much more impressive feat.
[src:home-run/home-run] He walked on four pitches in the second inning of game 6.
[src:home-run/home-run] Then he hit his three home runs on the first pitch of his next three at-bats, off three different pitchers (4th inning: Hooten; 5th inning: Sosa; 8th inning: Hough).
[src:home-run/home-run] He had also hit one in his last at-bat of the previous game, giving him four home runs on four consecutive swings.
[src:home-run/home-run] The four in a row set the record for consecutive homers across two Series games.
[src:home-run/home-run] In Game 3 of the World Series in 2011, Albert Pujols hit three home runs to tie the record with Babe Ruth and Reggie Jackson.
[src:home-run/home-run] Louis Cardinals went on to win the World Series in Game 7 at Busch Stadium.
[src:home-run/home-run] In Game 1 of the World Series in 2012, Pablo Sandoval of the San Francisco Giants hit three home runs on his first three at-bats of the Series.
[src:home-run/home-run] Nomar Garciaparra holds the record for consecutive home runs in the shortest time in terms of innings: three home runs in two innings, on July 23, 2002, for the Boston Red Sox.
[src:home-run/home-run] An offshoot of hitting for the cycle, a "home run cycle" is when a player hits a solo home run, two-run home run, three-run home run, and grand slam all in one game.
[src:home-run/home-run] This is an extremely rare feat, as it requires the batter not only to hit four home runs in the game but also to hit the home runs with a specific number of runners already on base.
[src:home-run/home-run] This is largely dependent on circumstances outside of the player's control, such as teammates' ability to get on base, and the order in which the player comes to bat in any particular inning.
[src:home-run/home-run] A further variant of the home run cycle would be the "natural home run cycle", should a batter hit the home runs in the specific order listed above.
[src:home-run/home-run] A home run cycle has never occurred in MLB, which has only had 21 instances of a player hitting four home runs in a game.
[src:home-run/home-run] Major league players have come close to hitting a home run cycle, two notable examples being Scooter Gennett of the Cincinnati Reds on June 6, 2017, and Mark Whiten of the St.
[src:home-run/home-run] Gennett hit four home runs against the St.
[src:home-run/home-run] He hit a grand slam in the third inning, a two-run home run in the fourth inning, a solo home run in the sixth inning, and a two-run home run in the eighth inning.
[src:home-run/home-run] He had an opportunity for a three-run home run in the first inning but drove in one run with a single in that at-bat.
[src:home-run/home-run] Whiten hit a grand slam in the first inning, a three-run home run in both the sixth and seventh inning, and a two-run home run in the ninth inning.
[src:home-run/home-run] In doing so, he also tied the MLB record for total RBIs in a game with 12.
[src:home-run/home-run] On Sept 8, 2024 Pavin Smith of the Arizona Diamondbacks hit 3 consecutive home runs versus the Houston Astros to have a shot at the Home Run Cycle.
[src:home-run/home-run] He hit a 3 run HR in the 2nd, a Grand Slam in the 3rd, and a solo HR in the 5th.
[src:home-run/home-run] He struck out with a man on base in his final at-bat.
[src:home-run/home-run] In the early days of the game, when the ball was less lively and the ballparks generally had very large outfields, most home runs were of the inside-the-park variety.
[src:home-run/home-run] The first home run ever hit in the National League was by Ross Barnes of the Chicago White Stockings (now known as the Chicago Cubs), in 1876.
[src:home-run/home-run] The home "run" was literally descriptive.
[src:home-run/home-run] Home runs over the fence were rare, and only in ballparks where a fence was fairly close.
[src:home-run/home-run] Hitters were discouraged from trying to hit home runs, with the conventional wisdom being that if they tried to do so they would simply fly out.
[src:home-run/home-run] This was a serious concern in the 19th century because in baseball's early days, a ball caught after one bounce was still an out.
[src:home-run/home-run] The emphasis was on place-hitting and what is now called "manufacturing runs" or "small ball".
[src:home-run/home-run] The home run's place in baseball changed dramatically when the live-ball era began after World War I.
[src:home-run/home-run] First, the materials and manufacturing processes improved significantly, making the now-mass-produced, cork-centered ball somewhat more lively.
[src:home-run/home-run] Batters such as Babe Ruth and Rogers Hornsby took full advantage of rules changes that were instituted during the 1920s, particularly the prohibition of the spitball, and the requirement that balls be replaced when worn or dirty.
[src:home-run/home-run] These changes resulted in the baseball being easier to see and hit, and easier to hit out of the park.
[src:home-run/home-run] Meanwhile, as the game's popularity boomed, more outfield seating was built, shrinking the size of the outfield and increasing the chances of a long fly ball resulting in a home run.
[src:home-run/home-run] The teams with the sluggers, typified by the New York Yankees, became the championship teams, and other teams had to change their focus from the "inside game" to the "power game" in order to keep up.
[src:home-run/home-run] Before 1931, Major League Baseball considered a fair ball that bounced over an outfield fence to be a home run.
[src:home-run/home-run] The rule was changed to require the ball to clear the fence on the fly, and balls that reached the seats on a bounce became automatic doubles (often referred to as a ground rule double).
[src:home-run/home-run] The last "bounce" home run in MLB was hit by Babe Herman of the Brooklyn Robins on September 23, 1930, at Ebbets Field.
[src:home-run/home-run] A carryover of the old rule is that if a player deflects a ball over the outfield fence in fair territory without it touching the ground, it is a home run, per MLB rule 5.05(a)(9).
[src:home-run/home-run] Additionally, MLB rule 5.05(a)(5) still stipulates that a ball hit over a fence in fair territory that is less than 250 feet (76 m) from home plate "shall entitle the batter to advance to second base only", as some early ballparks had short dimensions.
[src:home-run/home-run] Also until circa 1931, the ball had to go not only over the fence in fair territory, but it had to land in the bleachers in fair territory or still be visibly fair when disappearing from view.
[src:home-run/home-run] The rule stipulated "fair when last seen" by the umpires.
[src:home-run/home-run] Photos from that era in ballparks, such as the Polo Grounds and Yankee Stadium, show ropes strung from the foul poles to the back of the bleachers, or a second "foul pole" at the back of the bleachers, in a straight line with the foul line, as a visual aid for the umpire.
[src:home-run/home-run] Ballparks still use a visual aid much like the ropes; a net or screen attached to the foul poles on the fair side has replaced ropes.
[src:home-run/home-run] Babe Ruth's 60th home run in 1927 was somewhat controversial because it landed barely in fair territory in the stands down the right field line.
[src:home-run/home-run] Ruth lost many home runs in his career due to the when-last-seen rule.
[src:home-run/home-run] Bill Jenkinson, in *The Year Babe Ruth Hit 104 Home Runs*, estimates that Ruth lost at least 50 and as many as 78 in his career due to this rule.
[src:home-run/home-run] Further, the rules once stipulated that an over-the-fence home run in a sudden-victory situation would only count for as many bases as was necessary to "force" the winning run home.
[src:home-run/home-run] For example, if a team trailed by two runs with the bases loaded, and the batter hit a fair ball over the fence, it only counted as a triple, because the runner immediately ahead of him had technically already scored the game-winning run.
[src:home-run/home-run] That rule was changed in the 1920s as home runs became increasingly frequent and popular.
[src:home-run/home-run] Babe Ruth's career total of 714 would have been one higher had that rule not been in effect in the early part of his career.
[src:home-run/home-run] In the 2020s, it has become increasingly popular for Major League teams to celebrate home runs using some sort of prop.
[src:home-run/home-run] For example, allowing the player to wear or hold an item, such as a hat, helmet, jacket, sword, or trident.
[src:home-run/home-run] Major League Baseball keeps running totals of all-time home runs by the team, including teams no longer active (before 1900) as well as by individual players.
[src:home-run/home-run] Gary Sheffield hit the 250,000th home run in all of MLB history (according to the then-current definition of the major leagues, which excluded Negro league baseball) with a grand slam on September 8, 2008.
[src:home-run/home-run] Sheffield had hit MLB's 249,999th home run against Gio González in his previous at-bat.
[src:home-run/home-run] The all-time, verified professional baseball record for career home runs for one player, excluding the U.S.
[src:home-run/home-run] Negro leagues during the era of segregation, is held by Sadaharu Oh.
[src:home-run/home-run] Oh spent his entire career playing for the Yomiuri Giants in Japan's Nippon Professional Baseball, later managing the Giants, the Fukuoka SoftBank Hawks and the 2006 World Baseball Classic Japanese team.
[src:home-run/home-run] Oh holds the all-time home run world record, having hit 868 home runs in his career.
[src:home-run/home-run] In Major League Baseball, the career record is 762, held by Barry Bonds, who broke Hank Aaron’s record on August 7, 2007, when he hit his 756th home run at AT&T Park off pitcher Mike Bacsik.
[src:home-run/home-run] Only eight other major league players have hit as many as 600: Hank Aaron (755), Babe Ruth (714), Albert Pujols (703), Alex Rodriguez (696), Willie Mays (660), Ken Griffey Jr.
[src:home-run/home-run] Giancarlo Stanton holds the record for currently active MLB players with 453 as of the end of the 2025 season.
[src:home-run/home-run] The single-season record is 73, set by Barry Bonds in 2001.
[src:home-run/home-run] Other notable single-season records were achieved by Babe Ruth who hit 60 in 1927, Roger Maris, with 61 home runs in 1961, Aaron Judge, with 62 home runs in 2022, and Sammy Sosa and Mark McGwire, who hit 66 and 70 respectively, in 1998.
[src:home-run/home-run] Negro league slugger Josh Gibson's Baseball Hall of Fame plaque says he hit "almost 800" home runs in his career.
[src:home-run/home-run] The *Guinness Book of World Records* lists Gibson's lifetime home run total at 800.
[src:home-run/home-run] Ken Burns' award-winning series, *Baseball*, states that his actual total may have been as high as 950.
[src:home-run/home-run] Gibson's true total is not known, in part due to inconsistent record-keeping in the Negro leagues.
[src:home-run/home-run] The 1993 edition of the MacMillan *Baseball Encyclopedia* attempted to compile a set of Negro league records, and subsequent work has expanded on that effort.
[src:home-run/home-run] Those records demonstrate that Gibson and Ruth were of comparable power.
[src:home-run/home-run] The 1993 book had Gibson hitting 146 home runs in the 501 "official" Negro League games they were able to account for in his 17-year career, about one home run every 3.4 games.
[src:home-run/home-run] Babe Ruth, in 22 seasons (several of them in the dead-ball era), hit 714 in 2503 games, or one home run every 3.5 games.
[src:home-run/home-run] The large gap in the numbers for Gibson reflects the fact that Negro League clubs played relatively far fewer league games and many more "barnstorming" or exhibition games during the course of a season, than did the major league clubs of that era.
[src:home-run/home-run] In 1987, Joey Meyer of the minor league Denver Zephyrs hit the longest verifiable home run in professional baseball history.
[src:home-run/home-run] The home run was measured at a distance of 582 feet (177 m) and was hit inside Denver's Mile High Stadium.
[src:home-run/home-run] On May 6, 1964, Chicago White Sox outfielder Dave Nicholson hit a home run officially measured at 573 feet that either bounced atop the left-field roof of Comiskey Park or entirely cleared it.
[src:home-run/home-run] Major League Baseball's longest verifiable home run distance is about 575 feet (175 m), by Babe Ruth, to straightaway center field at Tiger Stadium (then called Navin Field and before the double-deck), which landed nearly across the intersection of Trumbull and Cherry.
[src:home-run/home-run] The location of where Hank Aaron's record 755th home run landed has been monumented in Milwaukee.
[src:home-run/home-run] The spot sits outside American Family Field, where the Milwaukee Brewers currently play.
[src:home-run/home-run] Similarly, the point where Aaron's 715th home run landed, upon breaking Ruth's career record in 1974, is marked in the Turner Field parking lot.
[src:home-run/home-run] May 2019 saw 1,135 MLB home runs, the highest ever number of home runs in a single month in Major League Baseball history.
[src:home-run/home-run] During this month, 44.5% of all runs scored were the result of a home run, breaking the previous record of 42.3%.
[src:home-run/home-run] In postseason play, the most home runs hit by a player for a career is Manny Ramirez, who hit 29.
[src:home-run/home-run] Jose Altuve (23), Bernie Williams (22), Derek Jeter (20), and Kyle Schwarber (20) are the only other players to hit twenty postseason home runs.
[src:home-run/home-run] Rounding out the top ten as of the end of the 2021 season are Albert Pujols (19), George Springer (19), Carlos Correa (18), Reggie Jackson (18), Mickey Mantle (18, all in the World Series), and Nelson Cruz (18).
[src:home-run/home-run] As for most home runs in one postseason, Randy Arozarena holds the record with ten, done in the 2020 postseason.
[src:home-run/home-run] Replays "to get the call right" have been used extremely sporadically in the past, but the use of instant replay to determine "boundary calls"—home runs and foul balls—was not officially allowed until 2008.
[src:home-run/home-run] In a game on May 31, 1999, involving the St.
[src:home-run/home-run] Louis Cardinals and Florida Marlins, a hit by Cliff Floyd of the Marlins was initially ruled a double, then a home run, then was changed back to a double when umpire Frank Pulli decided to review video of the play.
[src:home-run/home-run] The Marlins protested that video replay was not allowed, but while the National League office agreed that replay was not to be used in future games, it declined the protest on the grounds it was a judgment call, and the play stood.
[src:home-run/home-run] In November 2007, the general managers of Major League Baseball voted in favor of implementing instant replay reviews on boundary home run calls.
[src:home-run/home-run] On August 28, 2008, instant replay review became available in MLB for reviewing calls in accordance with the above proposal.
[src:home-run/home-run] It was first utilized on September 3, 2008, in a game between the New York Yankees and the Tampa Bay Rays at Tropicana Field.
[src:home-run/home-run] Alex Rodriguez of the Yankees hit what appeared to be a home run, but the ball hit a catwalk behind the foul pole.
[src:home-run/home-run] It was at first called a home run until Tampa Bay manager Joe Maddon argued the call, and the umpires decided to review the play.
[src:home-run/home-run] After 2 minutes and 15 seconds, the umpires came back and ruled it a home run.
[src:home-run/home-run] About two weeks later, on September 19, also at Tropicana Field, a boundary call was overturned for the first time.
[src:home-run/home-run] In this case, Carlos Peña of the Rays was given a ground rule double in a game against the Minnesota Twins after an umpire believed a fan reached into the field of play to catch a fly ball in right field.
[src:home-run/home-run] The umpires reviewed the play, determined the fan did not reach over the fence, and reversed the call, awarding Peña a home run.
[src:home-run/home-run] Aside from the two aforementioned reviews at Tampa Bay, the replay was used four more times in the 2008 MLB regular season: twice at Houston, once at Seattle, and once at San Francisco.
[src:home-run/home-run] The San Francisco incident is perhaps the most unusual.
[src:home-run/home-run] Bengie Molina, the Giants' catcher, hit what was first called a single.
[src:home-run/home-run] Molina then was replaced in the game by Emmanuel Burriss, a pinch-runner, before the umpires re-evaluated the call and ruled it a home run.
[src:home-run/home-run] In this instance though, Molina was not allowed to return to the game to complete the run, as he had already been replaced.
[src:home-run/home-run] Molina was credited with the home run, and two RBIs, but not for the run scored which went to Burriss instead.
[src:home-run/home-run] On October 31, 2009, in the fourth inning of Game 3 of the World Series, Alex Rodriguez hit a long fly ball that hit a camera protruding over the wall and into the field of play in deep right field.
[src:home-run/home-run] The ball ricocheted off the camera and re-entered the field, initially ruled a double.
[src:home-run/home-run] However, after the umpires consulted with each other after watching the instant replay, the hit was ruled a home run, marking the first time an instant replay home run was hit in a playoff game.
